DON'T.md: Avoiding AI Detection in Research Writing
This document summarizes why Turnitin flags content as AI-generated and defines the prohibited patterns you must avoid to keep your work authentic.
1. Why Turnitin Flags Your Work
Turnitin’s AI writing detection tool analyzes text for specific statistical signatures that are common in LLM outputs:
Perplexity: AI models write with very low perplexity—they choose the most statistically probable next word. If your text is "too predictable," it flags as AI.
Burstiness: AI models tend to produce uniform sentence structures and lengths. Human writing has "burstiness"—a mix of short, punchy statements and long, complex, nested thoughts.
Lack of Personal Trajectory: AI lacks a cohesive "personal research journey." It summarizes information without connecting it to the specific constraints, field data, or unique architectural challenges of your project.
2. The "Don't" List: What to Avoid
To ensure your writing passes as human-authored and technically rigorous, DO NOT do the following:
❌ Don't use "Filler" Connectives
Stop using generic transition phrases that act as structural padding.
Avoid: "It is important to note," "Furthermore," "In conclusion," "It is crucial to understand," "On the other hand," "To summarize."
Do: Use logical, direct flow. Let the technical facts connect themselves.
❌ Don't "Summarize-List" Sources
Do not write entries that function as a laundry list of what authors did.
Avoid: "Author A did X. Author B did Y. Author C did Z."
Do: Synthesize by conflict or complementarity. "While Author A suggests X, the throughput constraints found in Author B's work necessitate a different approach."
❌ Don't use Robotic Symmetry
Do not maintain a consistent sentence rhythm.
Avoid: Writing three sentences in a row that are all 15-20 words long.
Do: Break the rhythm. Use a complex, 40-word technical definition followed by a 4-word punchy claim.
❌ Don't hide behind Passive Voice
Do not use excessive passive construction, which makes your research sound like it happened in a vacuum.
Avoid: "The data was collected, and the model was trained."
Do: Assert ownership. "We collected the data and trained the model to observe latency under heavy node load."
❌ Don't neglect the "Real-World"
Do not write about technology as if it exists only in a lab.
Avoid: Generalizing technical benefits without mentioning the friction of the PDS (e.g., poor connectivity, hardware limitations, staff resistance).
Do: Always ground your technical design in the "pain points" of your specific research environment.
3. The Golden Rule
If you didn't think it, don't write it. If you use AI for a draft, you must rewrite it so thoroughly—adding your own specific project data, your own unique logic, and your own voice—that the AI's original statistical signature is destroyed.